1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,200
Il Consiglio della Diplomacia di Plenipotenzialità degli Stati Uniti

2
00:00:14,200 --> 00:00:17,820
sulla creazione di un Corpo Criminale Internazionale.

3
00:00:19,000 --> 00:00:23,440
Noi continueremo, questo mattino, ad ascoltare le declarazioni generali.

4
00:00:24,460 --> 00:00:28,860
Ci sono 20 representanti del Stato partecipando a inscrivere su la lista di oratori per questo

5
00:00:28,860 --> 00:00:29,760
mattino.

6
00:00:30,460 --> 00:00:34,920
Poi, dobbiamo dare la parola ai representanti delle organizzazioni intergovernmentali e

7
00:00:34,920 --> 00:00:37,000
delle organizzazioni non governamentali.

8
00:00:37,380 --> 00:00:43,200
In questo modo, abbiamo deciso prima che tutte le declarazioni generali di questo mattino

9
00:00:43,200 --> 00:00:45,980
devono essere realizzate all'interno del tempo previsto.

10
00:00:46,940 --> 00:00:54,700
Dobbiamo utilizzare il nostro tempo efficatamente e, soprattutto, dobbiamo abbracciare bene

11
00:00:54,700 --> 00:00:56,160
il vostro telefono portabile.

12
00:00:56,520 --> 00:00:57,240
Grazie.

13
00:00:58,020 --> 00:01:04,040
Avant de donner la parole au distingué représentant de l'Italie, puisse demander

14
00:01:04,040 --> 00:01:11,760
au prochain orateur, le distinguées représentantes de la Slovakie, de bien vouloir prendre place

15
00:01:11,760 --> 00:01:14,440
au siège réservé près du podium.

16
00:01:15,500 --> 00:01:18,420
Cha orateur doit se limiter à 7 minutes.

17
00:01:19,100 --> 00:01:21,620
Je prie de respecter ce limite.

18
00:01:24,120 --> 00:01:26,820
Allora, andiamo a cominciare.

19
00:01:27,220 --> 00:01:33,740
E dobbiamo dare la parola al distingué rappresentante dell'Italie.

20
00:01:34,620 --> 00:01:40,840
E io prendo il rappresentante della Slovakie che prende la posizione al siège.

21
00:01:41,920 --> 00:01:43,560
A sinistra.

22
00:01:43,760 --> 00:01:46,340
A sinistra del siège riservé.

23
00:02:01,860 --> 00:02:10,800
Mr. Chairman, distinguished delegates, this diplomatic conference marks the final stage

24
00:02:11,180 --> 00:02:17,660
in a process that began in the wake of the Second World War to institute a permanent

25
00:02:17,660 --> 00:02:20,220
international criminal court.

26
00:02:21,060 --> 00:02:29,060
It has been a long and gruelling path fraught with so many lost opportunities and marred

27
00:02:29,060 --> 00:02:32,800
by tragedies that have affected the whole of humanity.

28
00:02:34,360 --> 00:02:41,300
Rome is about to be the venue for a new step forward towards the acknowledgement of the

29
00:02:41,300 --> 00:02:49,860
respect due to human dignity and its effective protection, as it was in 1950 when the European

30
00:02:49,860 --> 00:02:56,880
Convention for the Protection of Human Rights and Fundamental Freedoms was signed here.

31
00:02:58,400 --> 00:03:06,520
Italy has long stood by those wishing to codify new rules for international coexistence and

32
00:03:06,520 --> 00:03:10,740
to guarantee compliance with them through appropriate instruments.

33
00:03:11,640 --> 00:03:18,180
For Italy, which is honoured to be hosting so many distinguished delegations, the establishment

34
00:03:18,180 --> 00:03:22,320
of the International Criminal Court is a top priority.

35
00:03:23,660 --> 00:03:31,400
We believe that we can contribute to it, drawing on Italy's centuries-old judicial tradition,

36
00:03:32,200 --> 00:03:40,180
her campaigns on civil issues and her public opinion, which is expecting a reaction to

37
00:03:40,180 --> 00:03:47,300
the many intolerable violations of human rights, and the horrors and hardships we have been

38
00:03:47,300 --> 00:03:52,480
witnessing to often as onlookers in recent years.

39
00:03:53,700 --> 00:04:01,200
Violence, grievous misdeeds and harassment perpetrated against individuals and whole

40
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:05,260
peoples are still in the conscience of our societies.

41
00:04:06,420 --> 00:04:08,840
They stand as a warning to us all.

42
00:04:09,780 --> 00:04:15,880
Fresh outbreaks of criminal deeds, which we believe to belong to the distant past, are

43
00:04:15,880 --> 00:04:22,360
making it all the more necessary, urgent, to institute an international criminal court.

44
00:04:23,500 --> 00:04:29,960
What our consciences and common sense demand is that we should put in place instruments

45
00:04:30,520 --> 00:04:37,060
that we will be able to prevent and mete out punishment for the most alteration crimes

46
00:04:37,060 --> 00:04:45,860
against international law, so that even when all the essential values are swept aside by

47
00:04:45,860 --> 00:04:53,300
war, the duties demanded by human solidarities are not ignored, so that we make it utterly

48
00:04:53,300 --> 00:04:59,780
clear to all that even in war, conduct is subject to rules and penalties.

49
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:07,480
Leaving crimes against humanity unpunished would signify the failure of the great efforts

50
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:15,740
that have been deployed since 1948 to translate solemn international declarations of principle

51
00:05:15,740 --> 00:05:19,520
into provisions of international criminal law.

52
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:26,920
Ever since that time, the proliferation of so many conventions and declarations of rights

53
00:05:26,920 --> 00:05:34,260
has stood in sinister and dramatic contrast to the proven inability to protect and safeguard

54
00:05:34,260 --> 00:05:41,480
the primary and most elementary rights of all, that is, the right of every human being

55
00:05:41,820 --> 00:05:43,860
to life and security.

56
00:05:45,160 --> 00:05:52,240
It is not enough for the international community to reach agreement on the conduct constituting

57
00:05:52,240 --> 00:05:59,180
international criminal offences, and authority is also necessary to prosecute them.

58
00:05:59,910 --> 00:06:06,440
The only way to prevent the likelihood of collective repression and to foster reconciliation

59
00:06:07,010 --> 00:06:16,060
is to institute an effective system to prosecute and convict the individuals who perpetrate

60
00:06:16,060 --> 00:06:16,860
these crimes.

61
00:06:18,300 --> 00:06:26,380
The court will not judge only in the name of the victors, and neither will the court be

62
00:06:26,380 --> 00:06:32,740
a tribunal occasionally set up in response to the wave of indignation against crimes

63
00:06:32,740 --> 00:06:35,160
that are committed from time to time.

64
00:06:35,960 --> 00:06:42,580
It must be a strong institution, with all the indispensable features needed to guarantee

65
00:06:42,580 --> 00:06:48,740
its credibility, with very broad participation to make its statute universal.

66
00:06:49,100 --> 00:06:57,360
It must be a court that is devoid of partisan pressure, independent, impartial, based on

67
00:06:57,360 --> 00:07:03,080
the principles of the right to fair trial and the right to judicial defense.

68
00:07:04,400 --> 00:07:07,900
The court must effectively complement national courts.

69
00:07:08,660 --> 00:07:15,900
No doubt the paramount roles of the domestic courts.

70
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:22,700
However, the international court must be given a jurisdiction to take cognizance in

71
00:07:22,700 --> 00:07:30,400
cases where domestic courts are either unwilling or unable to act effectively and appropriately

72
00:07:30,400 --> 00:07:34,420
and thereby bridge the void that this would create.

73
00:07:35,500 --> 00:07:41,640
From a substantive viewpoint, it is crucially important to identify the crimes falling within

74
00:07:41,640 --> 00:07:43,300
the jurisdiction of the court.

75
00:07:43,900 --> 00:07:50,720
We share the view that it would be better to limit its jurisdiction to the most high

76
00:07:50,720 --> 00:07:57,320
nose crimes committed in the context of an armed conflict, whether international or not.

77
00:07:58,320 --> 00:08:04,660
Notwithstanding that it is the United Nations Security Council which retains responsibility

78
00:08:04,660 --> 00:08:11,300
to ascertain aggression, the court should also be empowered to prosecute the crime of

79
00:08:11,300 --> 00:08:11,800
aggression.

80
00:08:12,600 --> 00:08:18,360
Failure to include this crime within the court's remit would deprive the new institution

81
00:08:18,360 --> 00:08:20,900
of one of its primary functions.

82
00:08:22,160 --> 00:08:30,100
In more general terms, the role and the specific peacekeeping and international security responsibilities

83
00:08:30,680 --> 00:08:35,040
vested in the Security Council must be safeguarded.

84
00:08:35,040 --> 00:08:41,700
For this reason, a solution must be found which will balance relations between the

85
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:48,520
Security Council and the court, ensuring that it can perform its judicial functions

86
00:08:48,520 --> 00:08:51,940
in total independence and without hindrance.

87
00:08:53,020 --> 00:09:00,240
An independent prosecutor must not only be empowered to institute proceedings when individual

88
00:09:00,240 --> 00:09:08,000
States or the Security Council reports a crime, but also to take the initiative to

89
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:10,180
start the investigation independently.

90
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:17,960
Moreover, the credibility of an international criminal court will depend primarily on the

91
00:09:17,960 --> 00:09:24,360
prior acceptance of its jurisdiction and not to its subsequent endorsement.

92
00:09:24,980 --> 00:09:30,640
This makes it essential for the court's jurisdiction to be triggered automatically

93
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:36,160
and be imposed on States by virtue of accession to the States alone.

94
00:09:37,420 --> 00:09:44,260
Without this kind of automatic jurisdiction, the court will remain an arbitration tribunal,

95
00:09:44,420 --> 00:09:51,620
operating solely according to the contingent political will and will be substantially incapable

96
00:09:51,620 --> 00:09:57,340
of preventing, pre-empting and punishing the crimes within its scope.

97
00:09:58,700 --> 00:09:59,740
Every State party

